{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_013SDVzCvLV9ExyN2voeuuaJ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the current state. Let me plan the implementation carefully.\n\nThe improvement plan has 4 changes:\n1. **Pre-merge continuation lines** before candidate generation (Change 1)\n2. **Ingredient-gap detection** in multi-title guard (Change 2)\n3. **First-line mixed-case title protection** (Change 3)\n4. **Eval harness fix** (Change 4 - in title-loop.py)\n\nLet me look at the iter.txt file to understand what's failing, and also check the title-loop.py for Change 4.\n\nLet me think through each change carefully:\n\n\nFor Change 1, I need to modify `buildCandidates` to pre-merge continuation lines before generating candidates. After finding `burstEnd`, I'll iterate through the remaining lines and merge any that have a continuation marker at the start of the next line, then use the merged result for candidate generation instead of the original array. I need to merge continuation lines before generating candidates, so the flow becomes: build nonEmptyLines, compute burstEnd from those, then merge lines that start with continuation characters, and finally generate candidates from the merged result. I'm realizing that merging only the portion after `burstEnd` is cleaner since the earlier lines are garbled anyway, and I need to preserve the original `.index` values for scoring—which the merge operation already handles by keeping the first line's index. Let me work through the implementation details.\n\nWriting the merge logic... Finishing the merge loop and then updating the candidate generation to reference the merged lines instead of the original array, making sure the 2-line and 3-line joins work correctly with the pre-merged data.\n\nNow I'm tracing through the test case to see how the merge affects the structural heading detection—when \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\" and \"/ COTTAGE 