t product and magnitude normalization affect the final similarity score. The alternative join \"TITLE FIRST PART / SECOND PART Ingredients\" would embed with a strong header component, giving it a low raw score that won't compete with the better candidate. Moving on to the ARAYES test case, I'm checking how the algorithm handles a recipe with two title lines followed by ingredients and content.\n\nFor the BAKED EGGS scenario, the pre-merge step correctly identifies the ampersand-prefixed line and combines it with the preceding title, creating a single merged entry that flows into the candidate generation process.\n\nRegarding the `survivingJoins` protection block, it remains in place for non-continuation 2-line joins even though it becomes less critical for continuation-character merges. With the new pre-merging logic, I need to verify how the existing \"SAFFRON-type\" test behaves—specifically whether the structural heading detection and the 2-line join continuation check still work as expected when pre-merging happens first. Since there's no continuation character found, `firstStructuralHeading` stays as the base heading \"TITLE FIRST PART / SECOND PART\" and gets the structural bonus applied. Now I'm checking the multi-line title test with Polish text to see how the merging handles titles split across multiple lines before the ingredients section. The regex for detecting garbled text only matches ASCII lowercase letters, so Polish characters like 'ś' slip through—meaning \"śmietanowym z pieczarkami\" passes the filter as a standalone candidate despite its low embedding score. But when joined with \"Kurczak w sosie\", the full title scores high because it matches the recipe words, so the test should still pass. Now checking the three-line title test where \"pomidorowym\" and \"i bazylią\" both start with lowercase letters that aren't continuation characters, so they won't merge.\n\nImplementing the mixed-case title protection logic... I need to verify that `threshold` is in scope and available for the filtering logic. Since it's computed before `selected` gets filtered, that checks out. Now I'm considering whether to add an additional `rawScore` guard to protect against false positives like category headers — the plan suggests checking if the position-0 candidate's raw score is within a reasonable range of the ALL_CAPS candidate's, but I should test whether this is actually necessary for the existing test cases first.\n\nFor the CHLEBEK test, I'm examining what happens with \"Lato | Dania główne\" at position 0. This string contains a pipe character and lowercase letters, so it would fail the hard filters check and wouldn't make it into `selected` in the first place. I'm checking each word in the candidate to see if it starts with a lowercase letter and has few ASCII characters—\"główne\" starts lowercase but after filtering non-ASCII characters like 'ł', it leaves enough letters that it doesn't count as garbled, so the overall string still passes the validation.\n\nNow I'm thinking through how Change 3 would affect the existing passing tests, particularly the Polish recipe test that picks a title over a section header—I need to verify whether \"Składniki\" would still be filtered out correctly or if the new garbling logic would interfere with the expected behavior. The embedding check confirms \"Składniki\" matches the header word list, giving it a low score of -0.8 that falls well below the threshold, so it gets filtered out. Now I'm moving to the next test case where multiple recipe titles should be selected when they both score well.\n\nFor the \"ARAYES SHRAK\" test, I'm checking whether the two-word ALL_CAPS phrase gets properly recognized as a structural heading and included in the selected results. ARAYES SHRAK\" is a 2-line join → IS a structural heading\n     - `firstStructuralHeading` = \"ARAYES SHRAK\"\n     - Prefix removal removes \"ARAYES\" (prefix of \"ARAYES SHRAK\")\n     - `selected` after prefix removal: likely \"ARAYES SHRAK\" only\n     - In Change 3: `pos0` = selected.find(s => s.position === 0 && !isAllCaps(s.text)). \"ARAYES SHRAK\" is ALL_CAPS. No mixed-case at pos 0. Change 3 won't fire.\n\n4. \"extends ALL_CAPS structural heading (SAFFRON-type)\":\n   - After pre-merging: \"TITLE FIRST PART / SECOND PART\" is the merged candidate\n   - It's ALL_CAPS at position 0 with no mixed-case text, so Change 3 won't trigger.\n\n5. \"preserves all-caps titles\":\n   - \"CHOCOLATE CAKE\" sits at position 0 in all caps, so Change 3 doesn't apply here either.\n\n6. \"picks title over section header (English)\":\n   - \"Ingredients\" appears at position 0 with mixed-case, but its embedding leans heavily toward header similarity, giving it a low score overall.\n   - It won't make it into `selected`, so Change 3 won't fire.\n\n7. Multi-title tests like \"returns multiple titles joined\" and \"two titles deep\":\n   - These typically don't have ALL_CAPS candidates, so Change 3 stays inactive.\n\nChange 3 looks safe across all existing tests. Now for the new test with \"Faszerowana papryka\": the first line is mixed-case at position 0, and the second line is all caps. I need to set up a mock embedding where \"Faszerowana papryka\" scores high enough to be treated as a title, then verify the expected output.\n\nWith Change 3 applied, \"Faszerowana papryka\" at position 0 would need a score above the threshold to stay in `selected`. The all-caps candidate \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" gets bonuses for being all caps and potentially the first structural heading, which could push its score higher. I need to calibrate the mock so \"Faszerowana papryka\" qualifies as the selected title.\n\nFor the test case, I'm thinking of a bilingual book scenario where the Polish title comes first with a moderate embedding score, and the all-caps transliteration comes second with a lower embedding score but higher structural bonuses. Change 3 should then filter out the all-caps version, leaving just the Polish title.\n\nWriting test case...\n\nNow I'm realizing that Change 3 strips ALL_CAPS subtitles regardless of their score, so even if \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" scores higher due to the capitalization bonus, the first-line protection should still eliminate it and leave \"Faszerowana papryka\" as the winner. I need to verify this logic doesn't create unexpected behavior when both candidates pass the threshold. I need to make sure \"Lato | Dania główne\" doesn't pass the embedding threshold since it's a category label rather than an actual dish title—with a properly tuned mock, its raw score should be low enough to filter it out naturally. For the CHLEBEK test, I'm designing it around an ALL_CAPS dish title with supporting ingredients, so the threshold logic should handle it correctly without needing extra guards. I'm working through the test structure for the ingredient-gap detection logic. The approach checks whether non-first ALL_CAPS headings are followed by ingredient content within a couple lines — if they are, they're marked as section headers rather than recipe titles. This lets me filter out the secondary heading while keeping the primary one. I'm tracing through how the ingredient detection works for the CHLEBEK example—checking whether \"500 g strączków\" would be recognized as an ingredient line by looking at measurement patterns and number prefixes. The logic checks out for CHLEBEK too—when the lines after the header contain ingredient measurements, it correctly identifies them as a sub-header and returns only the main title. I'm realizing I should simplify the test setup by controlling the input directly rather than worrying about edge cases like position-0 protection, and I need to verify where `allCapsSelected` gets sorted in the current implementation.\n\nNow I'm refining the multi-title guard to add an ingredient-gap check for the all-caps branch...\n\nI'm sorting the all-caps selections by position and checking if every non-first one is immediately followed by ingredient-like content or numbers, which would indicate they're section headers within the same recipe rather than separate recipe titles. If they all look like sub-headers, I keep only the first one; otherwise I keep all the all-caps selections. The `lines` variable is already in scope from the text split, so this should work.\n\nNow I need to look at the title-loop.py file and implement the other changes, particularly normalizing slashes and colons in the `titles_match` function. I should also check what new tests need to be added for the continuation merging case. Now I'm working through the exact placement of Change 3 — the first-line title protection rule needs to go after scoring, threshold filtering, prefix removal, and dedup, but before the multi-title guard kicks in. Let me verify this ordering makes sense with the existing flow.\n\nLooking at the test case, Change 3 should prevent the multi-title guard from incorrectly collapsing candidates when there's a legitimate first-line title. I also need to normalize colons and slashes in the comparison function for title-loop.py.\n\nNow I'm ready to implement these changes, starting with modifying buildCandidates to iterate over the correct line range...\n\nRefactoring the candidate loop... Continuing with the merged lines, I'm now iterating through them to test different joining patterns—single lines, pairs, and triplets—to find the best matches against the reference patterns.\n\nNow I need to add logic that protects mixed-case titles in the first position: if there's a reasonable-scoring mixed-case candidate at position 0 and only one ALL_CAPS option nearby, I'll treat that ALL_CAPS text as a subtitle and stick with the first-line title instead.\n\nThen for multiple ALL_CAPS candidates, I'm checking whether the ones after the first look like subheaders by examining if the following lines contain ingredient-like patterns or numbers, and if so, filtering down to just the primary one.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the test cases I need to add to validate these changes, starting with one that verifies continuation lines beginning with an ampersand get properly merged into the preceding line.\n\nFor the second change, I'm checking that when there are multiple ALL_CAPS headings, only the first one is treated as the title while subsequent ones are recognized as section headers followed by ingredient lists.\n\nNow I'm examining the edge case where \"CHLEBEK\" appears as a single-word ALL_CAPS heading later in the text. Since it's only one word, it won't qualify as a structural heading (which requires at least two words), but it could still be picked up as a candidate and potentially survive the threshold filtering.\n\nLooking at the hard filters: the word passes length checks, isn't a number or metadata, and has a reasonable vowel ratio (2 out of 7 letters), so it's not flagged as garbled. However, when checking against the actual title \"chlebek z warzywami i boczkiem\", the single word \"chlebek\" doesn't match the full title string, so it gets assigned a neutral embedding score and a lower raw score. Computing the similarity scores for the neutral embedding against the reference vectors, I get header and noise similarities of around 0.366 and 0.854 respectively, which gives a raw score of -0.488—well below the threshold, so \"CHLEBEK\" fails the filter. For \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\", it doesn't contain the full title phrase, so it also gets a neutral score and won't pass.\n\nBut wait, that's the issue—in the real scenario, both strings actually score above threshold with genuine embeddings, so I need to redesign the mock to reflect that reality. I'm setting up the mock embeddings so both \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" and \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" pass the threshold, which means Change 2 should then filter and keep only the first one.\n\nSetting up the mock embeddings...\n\nNow I'm verifying the logic: both options score high enough to pass, so `allCapsSelected` contains both. Change 2 kicks in, sorts them by position, and since the line after \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" starts with a digit, it correctly identifies that as a subheader and removes it, leaving only the main item.\n\nFor Change 3, I'm testing a bilingual scenario where a mixed-case Polish title sits above an all-caps Hungarian subtitle, and the algorithm should prefer the Polish version at position 0.\n\nNow I'm working through the logic for detecting all-caps text: checking if \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" qualifies as all-caps by examining the letter composition, then counting significant words (those with multiple uppercase letters) to determine if it looks like a structural heading rather than a natural title. \"Faszerowana papryka\" scores around 0.989 with position and matching bonuses, while \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" gets a rawScore of 0.883 with a position factor of 1.11, though it's missing the all-caps bonus I initially thought it would have.\n\nWait, let me recalculate—adding the structural bonus of 0.10 for being a first structural heading, \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" actually scores higher at around 1.160 compared to 0.989. Both easily clear the threshold of 0.674, so I need to check the multi-title guard to see if there's a conflict when Change 3 isn't applied.\n\nWith just one all-caps candidate, \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" wins outright. But when I apply Change 3, the logic removes it from consideration since it's all-caps and positioned early, leaving only \"Faszerowana papryka\" in the selected list. Now I need to verify whether both titles actually remain in the selected array after the prefix and suffix removal steps, since \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" is marked as the first structural heading.\n\nTracing through the deduplication logic: prefix removal doesn't affect either candidate, the survivingJoins block doesn't create any multi-line combinations, and the dedup step finds no substring relationships between them. Change 3 then filters out \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" because it's all-caps, leaving \"Faszerowana papryka\" as the final result. I should also check how the survivingJoins block handles edge cases with multi-line candidates.\n\nFor the SAFFRON test, pre-merging combines the split title into a single candidate, so survivingJoins has nothing to process. The mergedLines array still generates potential 2-line and 3-line joins, but I need to verify how the existing tests behave with this new structure.\n\nLooking at the candidates generated from mergedLines: the merged title passes hardFilters, the 2-line join with \"Ingredients\" also passes, but the 3-line join gets filtered out because it contains \"cup\" which triggers the ingredient detection. Then I'm checking how \"Ingredients\" itself gets evaluated.\n\nNow I'm working through the scoring logic for the merged candidate \"TITLE FIRST PART / SECOND PART Ingredients\" — it contains both title and header keywords, so the embedding classification returns balanced scores, and I'm calculating the rawScore using the normalization formula.\n\nThe score comes out to zero, which falls below the threshold, so it won't be selected. I'm also verifying that Change 3 won't trigger for the all-caps variant since the position-zero check requires a non-all-caps string, and this candidate is entirely uppercase.\n\nNow I'm working through the \"two titles deep\" scenario where the text contains multiple recipe sections with repeated \"Ingredients\" headers. I'm checking whether the burst-end detection correctly identifies \"Ingredients\" as a non-garbled word and confirming that no pre-merge conditions are met based on the line structure.\n\nLooking at the candidate titles like \"Pasta Carbonara\" and \"Tiramisu Classico\", both score highly because their words match the title word list. The multi-title guard logic checks if there are multiple selected candidates with all-caps text, but since there are no all-caps entries here, the guard doesn't trigger any filtering.\n\nFor scenarios where multiple titles are returned joined with a plus sign or separated by newlines, the same logic applies—if none of the candidates are in all-caps, the guard leaves them all intact. Change 3 won't activate in these cases either since there are no all-caps candidates to filter on.\n\nNow I'm checking how Change 3 interacts with the multi-title guard in the CHLEBEK test case. Both \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" and \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" are all-caps titles. After stripping the prefix, I need to evaluate whether the first one qualifies as a structural heading—it's all-caps with five words, but after filtering out single-letter words like \"Z\", the significant words are just \"CHLEBEK\", \"WARZYWAMI\", and \"BOCZKIEM\".\n\nBoth titles end up being structural headings with identical raw scores, so the first one wins as `bestStructural`. The continuation check then looks to see if \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" starts with the prefix of the first heading plus a continuation character, which it doesn't.\n\nAfter removing prefix candidates and checking for substring duplicates, neither title gets filtered out—\"warzywa i boczek\" isn't actually contained within \"chlebek z warzywami i boczkiem\" since the endings differ. Now I'm moving to the next change with pos0 selected.\n\nThe all-caps check filters out \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" since it's already uppercase, so that change doesn't apply. But the ingredient-gap logic kicks in for Change 2: since \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" is followed by a quantity starting with a digit, it marks this as a subheader and keeps just the first title. Let me verify this doesn't break the Finnish flatbreads case...\n\nLooking through the existing tests, I don't actually see a Finnish flatbreads test with all-caps titles. The current tests cover multiple titles joined with plus signs, but none specifically test that scenario, so the risk from Change 2 is only if that case comes up later.\n\nBut wait—the plan mentions \"4/8 currently passing,\" which refer