\"grams\" not in \"200g\"... actually the text is \"200g pasta\" which doesn't contain the full words \"gram\" or \"grams\". So looksLikeIngredient = false. So it passes hardFilters! This creates the candidate \"Pasta Carbonara 200g pasta\". Now I'm checking its score—it contains the titleWord \"pasta carbonara\" so it gets marked as a title, but I need to see what the final scoring looks like. I'm checking the dedup logic for \"Tiramisu Classico 250g mascarpone\" — it gets filtered out since the shorter \"Tiramisu Classico\" exists. Then I'm looking at \"Ingredients Pasta Carbonara\" in the candidate pool, which combines a header word with the title, giving it a score of 0 and keeping it below the threshold. So the \"two titles deep\" test should still pass. Now I need to verify the \"does not over-greedily join title with header\" test case...\n\nI'm setting up a test with \"Apple Pie\" as the title and \"Ingredients\" as a header, then checking what candidates get generated from multi-line joins. The candidates include the title alone, the title with the header appended, and even a three-line join that pulls in \"200g flour\". I'm verifying whether \"200g flour\" passes the hard filters — it starts with 'A' from \"Apple Pie\", so it fails the startsWithNumber check. Then I'm checking if \"flour\" matches any measurement patterns in the list, and it doesn't. there. So passes hardFilters.\n\n\"Apple Pie Ingredients\" → contains \"apple pie\" (title) AND \"ingredients\" (header) → [0.5, 0.5, 0]. rawScore = 0. Below threshold.\n\"Apple Pie Ingredients 200g flour\" → same → [0.5, 0.5, 0]. rawScore = 0. Below threshold.\n\"Apple Pie\" → high title score. In selected.\n\"Ingredients\" → header score → not in selected (or if it is, score < threshold).\n\"200g flour\" → startsWithNumber? No. But wait, \"200g flour\" → `passesHardFilters`: starts with '2' → digit → startsWithNumber = true → fails hardFilters. So not a candidate.\n\nResult: \"Apple Pie\" ✓\n\nNow testing the burst detection with a mix of short and long lines. I'm checking how the algorithm identifies when a burst of short lines ends by looking at line length and character patterns. For the test case with \"pg 42\", \"A.\", \"foo\" followed by a longer line, I'm evaluating whether these short lines get flagged as garbled based on their vowel ratios and consonant patterns. Now I'm checking whether the merged lines pass the quality filters—the longer line about burst detection is 53 characters, which clears the length requirement, but I need to verify it's not garbled by looking for patterns like mid-sentence periods or suspicious word formations. I'm ready to implement these changes. Let me verify the ingredient detection logic one more time—specifically how the function handles the Polish measurement \"g\" in \"500 g strączków\" and how it slices the lines array to check surrounding context for ingredient patterns.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4734,"cache_read_input_tokens":34510,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4734},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"52016906-9333-4309-a52f-615c04047092","uuid":"a6e0a5b3-aa84-4460-b2fe-ea29191131b7"}
